nd structure. Inspired by Raymond Williams's classic essay "Structures of Feeling" and influenced by the current discussion of affect studies, this collection inverts Williams's influential concept to explore the ephemerality of feeling as working in concert with the grounding forces of materiality and history. Feelings of Structure is a collection of twelve original texts that explores the weight of diverse encounters with a variety of configurations, be they institutional, spatial, historical, or fantastical. Featuring writers from a range of disciplines, this book aims for textual evocation in subject matter and approach, with essays that encompass multiple methodologies, writing styles, and tones. Experimental in nature, Feelings of Structure balances the need for concrete and specific observation with the ephemerality of experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAffect (Psychology). 0aEmotions. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh1 aCampbell, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarroch, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngle, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngle, Karen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFreeman, Lindsey A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcia, Christien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaasa, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLauder, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMair, Kimberly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodney, Lee, econtributor.4